    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-04T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-04T02:00:00-05:00" n="758"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d758">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/11624: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-04T09:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 4, 1941—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>187. British planes dropped a few bombs on army gasoline stocks in Beirut
                    yesterday and this morning. Today’s bombing seems to have done considerable
                    damage and I shall report details later. Population is remarkably calm and no
                    resentment is felt.</p>
                <p>I understand Germans are now withdrawing their airplanes and ground personnel
                    from Syria, including base at Aleppo, in order to make it appear that British
                    intervention is totally unwarranted and directed solely against the French and
                    natives.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Vichy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
